{% extends "_base.html.jinja" %}

{% block content %}
  {% with summary = {"title": "Cumulative Flow", "headline": cfd.headline} %}
    {% include "_partials/metric_summary.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  {% with mode = 'detail', data = cfd %}
    {% include "_partials/cfd_tile.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  <section class="detail-extras">
    <h2>How to read this</h2>
    <p>
      Each band is a stage in the workflow. The band's height at a
      given date equals the count of items currently in that
      stage (work in progress for that stage). Bands stack in
      workflow order from top to bottom — the first stage at the
      top, the terminal stage (departures) at the bottom. The
      total stack height = items currently in the system.
    </p>
    <p>
      Slope of the top boundary = arrival rate. Slope of the
      bottom boundary = throughput (departure rate). The
      horizontal distance between top and bottom at any date
      gives you approximate lead time. A widening middle band =
      a bottleneck stage piling up.
    </p>

    <h2>Caveats</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Stage workflow order is inferred from data using
        pairwise precedence — for every pair of stages, the one
        that more often comes earlier wins. Robust against items
        skipping a stage (e.g. PRs opened directly into Awaiting
        Review without ever being Draft). A future contract YAML
        override will let you pin the order explicitly.</li>
      <li>The time axis is clamped to the contract window
        (start → stop). Items that reached a stage BEFORE start
        are still counted at start — the math is unchanged, only
        the visible range is scoped.</li>
      <li>Items that skip a stage are counted as having "reached"
        that stage from the moment they entered any later stage.
        Without this, bands would cross — mathematically nonsense
        for a CFD.</li>
      <li>If the source emits the same stage twice for an item
        (ping-pong back to a prior state), only the first entry
        counts toward the cumulative. Flow cycling is a separate
        analysis.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      For each (date, stage), the value plotted is the cumulative
      count of items that have reached that stage or any later
      stage by that date. Stack in workflow order; the band heights
      are the per-stage differences. The bottom band's cumulative
      at the final date equals the count of completed items in
      the warehouse — a cross-check between transitions and
      work_items.
    </p>
  </section>

  <a class="back-link" href="{{ ("/workflows/" ~ contract.name ~ "/") | keep_filters }}">← Back to dashboard</a>
{% endblock %}
